Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. From January 2020 to September 2021 the Claimant Count in Trafford has increased a 73.1%. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 4.1% in September 2021 representing an increment of 1.8% from January 2020. The number of claimants has been decreased from April 2021.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in September 2021 was Clifford with 11.9% of all claimants within Trafford. All the wards have less claims in September 2021 compared to September 2020. Clifford has the largest reduction in number of claims with -200 followed by Altrincham (-130), Gorse Hill (-125) and Longford (-125).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in September 2021 were Clifford and Bucklow-St Martins with 8.1% and 7.9 respectably. The wards where the claimant rate has decreased more from September 2020 to September 2021 are Clifford with a decrease in rate of -2.3% followed by Bucklow-St Martins(-1.8%), Stretford(-2.3%) and Altrincham(-1.6%).

In Trafford from September 2020 to September 2021 almost all age bands have reduced their claimant count. When considering the reduction of claims the age band 18-24 years had the largest reduction with -495 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Trafford’s population within each age band shows a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others. The rate and count is decreasing for all age bands particularly for the the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34.

Almost half of Trafford’s claimants are residents of five of the 21 wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 34 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 87.2% from January 2020 to September 2021. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 11.5%. Therefore the number of Universal Credit claimants has almost doubled in that period.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in September 2021 was Old Trafford with 11.5% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. The MSOA with the highest percentage change from September 2020 to September 2021 were Gorse Hill, Firswood and Partington with 5% change. However, the MSOA with more additional claims in this period was Old Trafford and Partington with 64, followed by Gorse Hill (53) and Firswood (43).

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in September 2021 were Partington with 26.8% and Old Trafford with 24.2%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has grown more from September 2020 to September 2021 were Partington and Gorse Hill with 1.2% and 0.9% respectively along with Old Trafford and Firswood with 0.8%.

In Trafford from September 2020 to September 2021 the Over 65 age bands have the largest increment with 51% in the number of Universal Credit claims. When considering the number of additional claims from September 2020 to September 2021 the 5-year age band 60-65 years had the highest with 147 more claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from Mar 2020. All the age bands are increasing or maintaining their levels except for age band 16-24 that is decreasing steadily on rate and number of claims from April 2021.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the “Searching for Work” category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under “No work requirements”.
